export const batch105 = {
  'and-the-band-played-on.json': {
    base: { id: 'and-the-band-played-on', title: 'And the Band Played On', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781652525457 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Brave people step forward when disaster strikes',
        text: 'In the darkest hours of a spreading epidemic, a handful of courageous individuals stepped into the breach. Researchers on both sides of the Atlantic pushed forward with their work, even when funding was scarce and their reputations hung by a thread. In San Francisco, Dr. Selma Dritz, who served as assistant director of the Bureau of Communicable Disease Control, painstakingly logged cases of gay men suffering from a mysterious new illness. Her careful records of sexual histories gave later investigators a clearer picture of how the disease behaved.\n\nFrontline nurses and physicians cared for dying men even when prejudice surrounded them. Many patients themselves refused to fade quietly. Gary Walsh, a psychotherapist and one of those patients, organized a candlelight march that brought the crisis into public view.\n\nExtreme moments call for acts of courage that ordinary times never demand.\n\nThe warning signs that the catastrophe was accelerating turned out to be painfully accurate. Soon researchers realized the illness was reaching far beyond the gay community. Blood, not just sex, could pass the syndrome from one person to the next. Blood banks dragged their feet on screening, fearing the cost, and many infections slipped through during those lost years. The breakthrough came in 1983, when scientists identified HIV and confirmed that AIDS was a transmissible disease.\n\nA second group began showing symptoms: intravenous drug users. In the Bronx, immunologist Dr. Arye Rubinstein identified the disease in infants born to mothers with addiction.\n\nDr. Dale Lawrence added another chilling piece of the puzzle. His work on the incubation period suggested that five years could pass before symptoms emerged, meaning carriers had no warning of what waited inside them.\n\nAs Randy Shilts observed, madness wins the day when reasonable people choose silence.'
      },
      {
        title: 'The world before the storm',
        text: 'The mood in San Francisco in June 1980 felt almost triumphant. The Gay Freedom Day march filled the streets with a mix of celebration and remembrance, honoring a long history of persecution and hard-won progress. Religious leaders marched alongside artists and laborers, and the city pulsed with the energy of a community that had finally earned its place in the sun.\n\nNot everyone shared the optimism. A few voices pointed out that prejudice still shadowed daily life for many. The parade itself was a tribute to the Stonewall riot, when drag queens in Greenwich Village fought back against routine police raids on their gathering place. That moment had launched the modern liberation movement.\n\nThe newfound freedom soon fueled a sexual revolution centered on San Francisco. Visitors from across the globe arrived to live openly. The community also wanted to prove its civic worth, and gay men showed up in impressive numbers at the blood banks that rolled vans to major events. By 1980, gay donors supplied roughly seven percent of the city blood supply.\n\nSome disasters arrive without warning, yet preparation still matters.\n\nAlongside the pride came bathhouses, where the doors stayed open and the rules stayed loose. Within a single evening, a man might have many encounters. Before 1980, those spaces felt like pure liberation. Nobody imagined that death was already waiting behind the steam and the music.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A strange new illness appears',
        text: 'The alarm rang in 1981, when doctors in a handful of cities started seeing young, otherwise healthy men with rare conditions. Kaposi sarcoma and pneumocystis pneumonia both attack people whose immune systems have collapsed. Almost every patient was a gay man with an active sex life. The pattern was too unusual to ignore.\n\nDr. Michael Gottlieb, one of the first to grasp the stakes, teamed up with colleague Joel Weisman to publish a short report on pneumocystis carinii pneumonia in the CDC weekly newsletter. That brief article marked the first official recognition of the crisis. The Task Force on Kaposi Sarcoma and Opportunistic Infections, formed to study the outbreak, weighed two main theories. One held that poppers, the inhalants popular in clubs and bathhouses, were to blame. The other warned that a new infectious agent was on the loose.\n\nSexual orientation colored every debate that followed. Researchers knew epidemics do not pick victims based on identity, yet the early cases all clustered in the gay community. The CDC report avoided the word homosexual in its headlines, but gay newspapers had no such hesitation and shortened the diagnosis to Gay Pneumonia.\n\nEvery person deserves safety, no matter who they love.\n\nFurther study pointed to a virus passed through sex, later called HIV. For a time, the syndrome was called GRID, short for Gay Related Immune Deficiency. Once it became clear that heterosexual people could also fall ill, the name changed to AIDS, Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome.\n\nPrejudice, Randy Shilts wrote, imprisons both the person who hates and the person who is hated.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Years of missed chances',
        text: 'The opening phase of a major outbreak is always critical, and the world mostly wasted it. The AIDS crisis was ignored at every level, from the halls of government to the front page of the newspaper, and the price was counted in lives. Several factors slowed the response.\n\nFirst, money was tight. 1980 brought deep cuts to public health budgets. Researchers pleaded for funds, and officials did not move until the threat could no longer be denied. Second, prejudice kept many scientists from looking closely at the lives of gay men, even when the data begged them to. Third, once the funding finally arrived, some researchers treated the disease as a career opportunity rather than a shared emergency. Fourth, certain gay leaders put political ideals ahead of public health, fearing that closing bathhouses would hand critics a weapon against the community. Finally, the press stayed largely silent, treating the topic as too uncomfortable for a general audience.\n\nSpeed and cooperation decide whether a crisis is contained.\n\nHistory offered a clear counterexample. When Legionnaires disease broke out, the CDC spent nine million dollars in its first year. AIDS research received barely one million. The difference in funding was not about medical judgment. It was about who the disease affected and who decided to look away.\n\nAccording to UNAIDS, around 1.3 million people acquired HIV in 2022.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Heroes of the AIDS war',
        text: 'Even as institutions faltered, individuals stepped up. Scientists in the United States and Europe kept working through underfunded programs and the risk of professional ruin. In San Francisco, Dr. Selma Dritz, the assistant director of the Bureau of Communicable Disease Control, kept meticulous records of gay patients and their sexual networks. Her files became a key reference for later breakthroughs.\n\nPhysicians and nurses sat with men who were dying, often at personal cost. Patients themselves refused to disappear. Gary Walsh, a gay therapist, organized a candlelight march that put the epidemic on the front pages for the first time.\n\nIn a crisis this size, ordinary rules stop applying.\n\nSoon the truth spread. The syndrome was passing not only through sex but also through blood, a fact the blood banks resisted admitting. Donors were not screened in those early years, and infections multiplied. The picture changed in 1983, when researchers identified HIV and confirmed the disease was transmissible.\n\nA new population started showing symptoms: intravenous drug users. In the Bronx, Dr. Arye Rubinstein, an immunologist, identified the syndrome in babies born to addicted mothers.\n\nDr. Dale Lawrence work on the incubation period delivered another blow. He discovered that the virus could sit silent for five years before symptoms appeared, leaving carriers with no warning of what lay ahead.\n\nAs Randy Shilts put it, insanity won because the sane stayed quiet.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Facing the truth at last',
        text: 'Five years into the epidemic, neither the public nor most policymakers understood the full scope of the crisis. People were dying in steady numbers, and there was still no treatment and barely any money. Then the actor Rock Hudson announced that he had AIDS, and the headlines finally changed. The press stressed that the disease had crossed into the broader population, even as they reminded readers that Hudson was gay. What really shifted the story was that he was also famous and wealthy, two categories the public had not expected to see on an AIDS ward.\n\nNewspaper features profiled the rich and the well connected, but the underlying crisis stayed unsolved. The breakthrough came from Dr. C. Everett Koop, the surgeon general. Throughout 1986, he interviewed scientists, public health officials, and even skeptical gay leaders. Without White House approval, he released a blunt report that tackled the most painful questions head on, from sex education to the right of patients to keep their test results private.\n\nDisasters must be faced. Lessons must be drawn. Then, slowly, life goes on.\n\nWhat made the report land was not its timing, which was five years late, but the authority of the man writing it. The report was a turning point. The world began to register the scale of the disaster.\n\nIn Europe, governments launched education campaigns about safe sex and drug use. In the United States, a national AIDS commission was formed. The meetings stopped being only scientific and started mixing science with politics, the combination that the crisis had always required. The problem was far from solved, but at last it had been seen. Hope crept back that the long nightmare might end.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'The AIDS epidemic traces a path through the five stages of grief on a global scale. Denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance played out across governments, newsrooms, and living rooms. Society found it easier to look away for years, and the cost was enormous. People died without hope. AIDS was the killer, but silence and neglect were the accomplices. The story is a reminder that trouble caught early can be fought, and trouble ignored becomes catastrophe.\n\nPractical steps include reading the Immune summary to learn how the body fights infection and how to support it, scheduling a yearly checkup with your doctor, avoiding casual sex and using protection, and being willing to ask a partner about their history before getting close.\n\nKeep reading to the end.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'andy-warhol-was-a-hoarder.json': {
    base: { id: 'andy-warhol-was-a-hoarder', title: 'Andy Warhol Was A Hoarder', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781647493456 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Brilliance and struggle often share the same address',
        text: 'A stubborn myth says that high intelligence goes hand in hand with mental illness. In reality, every exceptional person develops their own way of working through problems. Autism used to be treated as nothing more than a learning disability, but research now shows that many people on the spectrum think in ways that are remarkably sharp. Great minds tend to treat the impossible as a starting point, and they hold on to that belief even when others laugh. Mental illness is real, and it can shadow even the brightest life. This summary is about both gifts and pain, and how often they appear together.\n\nFear is built into our evolution. Anxiety is not. Anxiety tends to settle in and stay.\n\nMental illness comes in every shape and severity, and it does not care about rank or reputation. Anyone can struggle, from an ordinary citizen to a president or a famous scientist.\n\nMillions of people live with at least one mental health condition, and many never get a diagnosis. Addictions to gambling, alcohol, sex, food, or other substances are common forms those conditions can take.\n\nClaudia Kalb weaves a careful narrative about several remarkable figures from different walks of life. Her writing gives a clear, humane account of how mental illness can shape a person, and it does so with a steady hand and a good ear.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Marilyn Monroe: the woman behind the smile',
        text: 'In 1962, Marilyn Monroe was booked to sing a personal song for President John F. Kennedy on his birthday. Within months of that performance, she was dead. At the height of her fame, she stood for beauty and charm, and her rumored link with the president only made her more visible.\n\nBehind the cameras, she was lonely and quietly unwell. Childhood trauma had left her with schizophrenia and borderline personality disorder, and she wrestled with emptiness and unstable relationships for years. The dark corners of her past refused to let go, and depression was a constant companion.\n\nDepression does not care about money, fame, or status. It can land on anyone.\n\nBorderline personality disorder can run in families, and it makes its victims prone to emotional pain, depression, and in the worst cases, suicide.\n\nDepression and anxiety often appear together, and they travel with addiction, autism, and eating disorders, as Claudia Kalb has written.\n\nTreating borderline personality disorder is hard because the patient is often defensive and quick to take offense. Therapy was never going to be enough for Marilyn Monroe. On August 5, 1962, she was found dead in her apartment, and her death was ruled a probable suicide.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Howard Hughes and the weight of OCD',
        text: 'Howard Hughes held pilot and producer credits and was considered among the best in both fields. His focus and discipline set him apart, but they also set him up for collapse. He lived with obsessive compulsive disorder, a condition that made him obsessed with order, germs, and routine. His mother had shared his fear of contamination, and it had rubbed off on him. He would avoid shaking hands and keep his distance from people whenever he could.\n\nStress and anxiety fueled his OCD, and the deaths of his parents made it worse. Before long, the condition started controlling the people around him as well.\n\nHis World War I epic, Hell Angels, took three years to finish because he kept cutting and re-editing the script. His insistence on perfection led to the death of one of his aircraft mechanics. The film cost roughly four million dollars by the time he was done.\n\nThe toll of OCD is real. It is a kind of mental suffering that can push people toward despair, self harm, and suicide.\n\nMost people with OCD know they make others uncomfortable, and they often do not know how to stop. Howard Hughes was caught in exactly that trap, and he died a lonely death at seventy.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Andy Warhol and the pull of hoarding',
        text: 'Plenty of people find it nearly impossible to throw things away. Clutter piles up because the idea of letting go feels worse than the mess, a habit that Marie Kondo wrote about in her book The Life Changing Magic of Tidying Up.\n\nAndy Warhol, the American artist, producer, and filmmaker, was a textbook hoarder. After his death, his home was found to be stuffed with objects that had no purpose, and in 2013 the space was turned into a museum.\n\nWarhol bought whatever he could lay his hands on. Some of his purchases were never opened. They were not needed. They were simply more things to keep.\n\nClutter adds nothing to a life. If you are not careful, it can quietly take over.\n\nWarhol disorder complicated his life. In 1968, Valerie Solanas shot him, and he survived the bullet wound to his torso. In later years he refused x-rays out of fear that he might pick up cancer or HIV. He died on February 22, 1987, after a post surgical heart attack.\n\nThe Autism and Developmental Disabilities Monitoring Network estimates that about one in fifty four children has been identified with autism spectrum disorder.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Princess Diana and the hidden pain of bulimia',
        text: 'Princess Diana wedding to Prince Charles looked like a fairy tale, but the marriage was something she would later come to regret. It was a long, painful chapter she wished she could have skipped.\n\nWatching her parents divorce as a child left her anxious, and she turned to food for comfort. That pattern grew into bulimia. Her engagement to Charles only made it worse.\n\nThe trouble with overindulgence is that it gets in the way of a child learning to handle the ordinary ups and downs of life, Claudia Kalb has noted.\n\nAfter Charles made a comment about her waistline, Diana lost a great deal of weight in a matter of months. The publicity around his relationship with Camilla Parker Bowles made everything harder.\n\nNot every kind of depression shows on the surface. People can keep smiling while carrying a heavy weight inside.\n\nBulimia is a cycle of bingeing, eating a lot in a short time, and purging, getting rid of what was eaten. As a royal, Diana had to hide her pain and play the part of a happy duchess. Unlike anorexia, bulimia does not always make people look thin, and the suffering was invisible. The condition can feed into borderline personality disorder, and Diana carried the damage until she could not. She died in a car crash on August 31, 1997, leaving a wish that others would look past her smile and notice the struggle she had been carrying.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Abraham Lincoln and the long shadow of depression',
        text: 'Abraham Lincoln, the sixteenth president of the United States, is remembered for his warmth and steady humor. He lost his mother at nine, lost two of his sons to illness, and shouldered the weight of nearly 620,000 American deaths during the Civil War.\n\nThe Great Depression drained him. His marriage added to the strain. Mary Lincoln, sometimes called Hellcat at the White House, was volatile, and Lincoln would sometimes leave in the middle of the night to clear his head.\n\nDepression has no respect for rank or power. Even the most powerful leader in the world could not escape the grief that piled up after losing so many people close to him.\n\nDepression can feel like drowning. Left untreated, it often leads to self harm and thoughts of suicide.\n\nLincoln life is a reminder that depression can reach anyone, even in the middle of great responsibility. He lived with suicidal thoughts for years and was finally killed by an assassin bullet in 1865, shot by John Wilkes Booth in a theater.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Christine Jorgensen and a new kind of courage',
        text: 'George Jorgensen decided to live as a woman set off a conversation that the world is still having. He set sail from New York Harbor on May 1, 1950, on a mission to fix what he called a mistake of nature.\n\nGeorge had never fit the mold expected of boys. He preferred the company of girls, their toys, and their games, and he could not see why he had to act tough, play sports, or hold back his tears just because he was male.\n\nHe spent years trying to figure out whether his struggle was psychiatric, hormonal, or both. He disliked his body, and when he chose to have gender affirming surgery, he knew he was making a decision that would change the rest of his life.\n\nIn Denmark, he met Dr. Christian Hamburger, an endocrinologist who offered to perform the procedures for free. Three years later, George returned to the United States as Christine Jorgensen, a woman at ease in her own skin.\n\nPeople who feel at odds with themselves often pull away from others, and they lose the chance to give and receive love.\n\nChristine lived openly shifted the way many people thought about gender. Transgender individuals feel that the sex they were assigned at birth does not match who they are. That mismatch can lead to despair and confusion, and those who cannot get help often end up in denial, afraid of what others might think.\n\nChristine Jorgensen died of bladder and lung cancer a few weeks before her birthday in 1989, and she had lived a full and honest life.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Frank Lloyd Wright and the grip of narcissism',
        text: 'Frank Lloyd Wright was a true original. He invented new forms in architecture and gave the field a fresh sense of life. Some of his buildings stretched the limits of what seemed possible.\n\nWright was also consumed by his own ego. He was a textbook narcissist, uninterested in the feelings or concerns of the people around him. In June 1943, he took on the job of designing a museum for Solomon Guggenheim modern art collection in New York.\n\nWright designed mostly for himself, not for the people who would use his buildings. He dismissed criticism easily, since he was sure he was right.\n\nNarcissism has many causes in the modern world. With smartphones, social media, and constant connection, it has never been easier to chase approval and tune others out.\n\nLike any illness, narcissism slowly wears its victims down until they cannot keep going.\n\nThe Guggenheim took sixteen years to finish, and even though it is now a landmark, many architects believe the building could have been more practical with a few changes.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Betty Ford and the trap of addiction',
        text: 'Betty Ford, the wife of President Gerald Ford, fought alcoholism that ran in her family. Her father had the same problem, and her own drinking was made worse by mixing alcohol with pills. Insecurity and a streak of sadness pushed her toward the bottle, and even when she saw what it was doing to her life, she could not stop.\n\nAlcoholism touches a huge number of people. Heavy drinkers tend to invent reasons for their behavior, blaming bad experiences or stress for their need to drink.\n\nDenial and enabling are common in alcoholism, and they make it hard for the person affected to ask for help. Either the addiction is denied or the drinking is justified.\n\nAlcohol and drugs act on the part of the brain that handles pleasure. When a slip turns into a relapse, the brain reaches for the same chemical reward, and the cycle restarts.\n\nAlcoholism is a biological condition, not a choice, and it takes time and help to undo.\n\nBetty Ford began to recover after she agreed to seek treatment. As she found ways to speak out about the issues that mattered to her, she grew more confident and faced her addiction directly.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Many things can set off a mental health condition. Anxiety is one of the most common. It is a fear of what might happen, and in its worst forms it bends every situation toward the worst possible outcome. Charles Darwin lived with anxiety, and the physical symptoms, including pain, palpitations, and stomach trouble, were his constant companions.\n\nFear is a passing visitor that everyone meets. Anxiety is a tenant that moves in and takes over the mind.\n\nMental health conditions shape how we connect with others, and they can cut us off from the people we love. People with autism, for instance, often find social contact difficult. They can come across as blunt or even rude, and they may call out mistakes without softening them. Autism can be exhausting for everyone involved, but it has also been a launching pad for greatness, as the example of Albert Einstein shows.\n\nGambling is another condition that has grown sharply in recent years. Gamblers tend to believe they can outsmart the system, and when they win, they often press their luck until the win is gone.\n\nNo one is immune, and mental illness can hurt the people around the sufferer as much as the sufferer themselves.\n\nPractical steps include searching the Headway app for more summaries about mental health, and a good place to start is Marie Kondo book on tidying. Avoid hostility toward people who need help, and consult a doctor for advice about yourself or the people in your life.\n\nKeep reading to the end.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'animal-vegetable-miracle.json': {
    base: { id: 'animal-vegetable-miracle', title: 'Animal, Vegetable, Miracle', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781647588413 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Small daily choices shape the body you live in',
        text: 'Do you ever read the label on a bag of chips, even from a familiar store? If you did, would it change what you buy? Probably not. The idea of making chips at home can sound intimidating, but the process is simpler than most people expect.\n\nModern life moves fast. Fast fashion, fast food, and fast schedules have all become normal. Everyone wants a quick fix, and food has not been spared. The cost shows up in the economy, in the land, and in our bodies. Treating both the planet and ourselves this way is not sustainable.\n\nSo what can you actually do? Growing some of your own food is a good start, and it is not as hard as it sounds. It is a reliable way to know what is going into your meals and to make sure the ingredients are high quality. With a little practice, the routine becomes natural and the rewards multiply.\n\nChildren learn good habits when adults show them, again and again, why local food matters.\n\nBarbara Kingsolver, her husband Steven Hopp, and their two daughters Camille and Lily left Arizona for rural Appalachia in search of a more honest way of eating. This summary follows that journey and shows how the lessons can fit into your own life.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Farming is everyone\'s business',
        text: 'Food does not come from a tidy aisle in a store, but that is how many children think of it. The truth is that someone, somewhere, had to plant the seed, tend the soil, and bring in the harvest. The skill of growing food is quietly disappearing as more families move to cities and more students are pushed toward office jobs.\n\nMost people pay little attention to the farmers behind their meals. Since the industrial revolution, farms have been producing roughly 3,900 calories per US citizen every day, helped along by synthetic fertilizers and a switch from natural systems to mechanical ones. We eat a lot of those calories without realizing it.\n\nAmerican food culture follows the tastes of the wealthy. Evolution has nudged us toward calorie dense foods, the kind that are rich in fat but not always rich in nutrition. Eating disorders are now common in this generation, and the average child may live a shorter life than their parents. Most people agree that fruits and vegetables should make up a bigger share of the diet, yet government subsidies still go to commodity crops that are not the healthiest choice.\n\nRates of anorexia, bulimia, and binge eating are all climbing in this generation, and the food culture around us is part of the reason.\n\nBanning certain foods is not enough on its own. A healthier food culture should pull us closer to the land that produces what we eat. It encourages us to live on the land, to think of soil and food in the same breath, and to ask where our groceries actually come from.\n\nThanks to the industrial revolution and changes in farming, humans now eat more calories than at any point in history.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A healthy lifestyle is hard at first, and worth it',
        text: 'Growing food means juggling a long list of projects. The garden needs work, the kitchen needs work, the pantry needs work, and the rhythm changes with the seasons. Trees grow differently in a new region, and so does the snow.\n\nIt helps to study the local climate and soil before deciding what to plant and when to plant it.\n\nA well-tended garden can easily feed an average American family, but building a garden that can carry a household through the year is real work, and the land itself has to cooperate. Patience and restraint are the two virtues that keep a gardener going.\n\nPutting together a grocery list gets tricky when everything has to come from the area. Most families can agree on a few small luxuries that are not local, and the goal is to keep everyone happy. Whether the budget covers a treat or not, the guiding principle is to choose what gives the household the most joy. It can be hard to please every family member, and the way to handle that is to make sure everyone has a seat at the table.\n\nMany people say they do not have time to grow food, and the statement is fair. The next move, though, is not to grab the nearest packaged meal. Cooking has become a lost art in many places, and the culture suffers for it.\n\nTime spent on a career or on entertainment often comes at the cost of time spent in the kitchen. People are busier than they used to be, and yet cooking can be folded into a daily routine and treated as part of the fun. It builds a habit that saves time, and it builds a tradition for the family. The benefits of cooking at home easily outweigh the appeal of eating out.\n\nHome cooked meals lead to better eating habits, sharper kitchen skills, and a smaller grocery bill.\n\nBuying local food also strengthens the community. Children grow up with a sense of where their food comes from, and they carry those values forward.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Protect the food crops we still have',
        text: 'The human diet draws on a huge number of plant species, but over time the variety has narrowed. Most of what people eat now comes from about eight crops. The shift happened in part because plant varieties started being treated as patentable property instead of as food. Scientists have engineered many crops, giving some a bacterial gene that kills pests, and tweaking others so they can survive herbicides.\n\nSo much food is processed today that some of it has lost much of its original value.\n\nDisease pathogens and their host plants keep evolving together, and either side can disappear, leaving the other to find new ways to attack or defend. The result is a food system that leans heavily on a small number of crops like corn and soy. To push back, some growers preserve rare varieties, plant them, and sell them across borders so the species keep circulating.\n\nEven non farmers have a role to play. One step is to look for the farmers who still grow these rare varieties and to buy from them regularly. Talking about how a plant tastes, and how it was prepared, can pull in new customers and give growers a reason to keep planting. The farmers, the customers, and the crops all win.\n\nLocal growers can produce some of the highest quality food available.\n\nWeeds are a regular challenge for farmers. They can be useful at times and destructive at others. Most conventional growers spray chemicals to control them, but organic growers avoid sprays, which is part of the difficulty. On a large operation where mulching is impractical, organic farmers rotate fast growing cover crops across three to four year cycles, giving weeds a chance to sprout.\n\nThey then till the weeds under before planting the main crop. That method makes it hard to grow on a large scale, so many organic farmers produce only for their own families. The few who manage to grow enough to sell are worth supporting, and there are simple ways to help: buy from them, tell others about them, and keep farm supplies affordable.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Every meal is a chance to support your community',
        text: 'Most of the non animal food we eat comes from flowering plants. The few exceptions include pine nuts, seaweed, and mushrooms. Most vegetables follow a one year cycle. They are planted in spring and harvested in the fall, and we tend to eat more than the planet can comfortably produce for the generations that follow.\n\nBuying from local growers keeps grocery dollars in the neighborhood and gives small businesses a chance to grow.\n\nSmall choices, like picking up local produce at the market, can add up to a real contribution. There is a steady demand for customers who will choose local over imported, and the decision is good for the local economy and for the environment at the same time.\n\nLocal farming takes a lot of labor, and the trade off in environmental and health terms is well worth the effort.\n\nLocal growers also depend on the seasons, and that rhythm does not always line up with a fast moving economy. The garden is quieter in winter, but there is still work to do. Weeds need pulling, compost needs turning, and beds need preparation. In the last decade, more than three hundred farms have disappeared every week in some regions. For some, the loss is final. For those who keep going, the recipe is a mix of luck, courage, and the willingness to adapt. Farmers who want to grow their business need to make their products affordable and available to middle income customers.\n\nSeveral studies, including research by Allison Byrum of the American Chemical Society, have shown that fruits and vegetables grown without pesticides and herbicides contain roughly fifty to sixty percent more antioxidants than their sprayed counterparts, as Barbara Kingsolver has noted.\n\nRaising food without polluting the land will always cost more than the cheapest path through industrial farming, and Americans still want to spend as little as possible at the grocery store. That tension is part of the reason for poor eating habits. Many people choose what looks cool over what is good for them, and studies show that a steady diet of cheap fast food leads to weight gain and a higher risk of diabetes. Organic farming is more labor intensive, and the relationships, the trust, and the quality that come with it are part of what makes local food worth the effort.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Seasonal eating starts with seasonal planning',
        text: 'Temperature shapes what the land can grow at any time of year, and careful planning at the start of the season pays off in every month that follows.\n\nEven though it is tempting to stock up at the store, it is possible to plan a garden that supplies a household for most of the year. The first step is to start planting in March, as soon as the soil begins to warm. Asparagus is a good early crop, since it grows in many regions and pairs well with all kinds of meals. By April, the first plants should be coming in. Cabbage, onions, potatoes, and kale tend to be ready in the warmer weeks of late spring.\n\nSummer is for parties, for cooking, and for putting food by. Many fruits ripen in autumn, which is also the time when meat can be cured and stored for the cold months. Winter is quieter, and the kitchen turns into a place to enjoy what was set aside during the busier seasons.\n\nThe seasons also change what the body wants. In winter, for instance, warm stews are often what feels right.\n\nLiving near cold water opens up another option. People in coastal regions can lower their risk of depression and bipolar disorder by eating more local fish, which is rich in Omega 3 fatty acids. Winter is also a good time to bake, since the heat from the oven helps warm the kitchen.\n\nSeasonal eating is not just healthier. Cooking at home through the year also trims the grocery bill, and it gives the family a reason to gather around the table. Even people who could earn more in other jobs can find real pleasure in cooking and canning.\n\nCooking is eighty percent confidence, a skill best learned from the time the apron ties cross at the back, as Barbara Kingsolver has written.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Farming is no longer the work of straw hatted families with no other choice. Anyone can bring locally grown food into daily life, and the habit pays back in health, in the local economy, and in the health of the environment.\n\nGrowing your own food solves several problems at once. You eat more fresh fruits and vegetables. You decide which fertilizers and pesticides, if any, come near your meals. You choose when to harvest and what quality to accept.\n\nIn short, you are in charge of what you eat from start to finish.\n\nYou are what you eat, so it is worth being thoughtful about where the food comes from. A small plot in the suburbs is enough to start a garden where things grow and the household is happier.\n\nBeyond growing your own food, you can support the organic farmers who work hard to feed their communities and rarely get the recognition they deserve. Buying at a farmers market, or choosing a local restaurant over a fast food chain, is a small vote in favor of better food systems. That kind of choice, multiplied across a community, is part of how the world gets healthier.\n\nPractical steps include learning which plants grow best in your region and starting a small garden with crops you actually want to eat. If your space is limited, support local farmers and cook more meals at home.\n\nKeep reading to the end.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'antiracist-baby.json': {
    base: { id: 'antiracist-baby', title: 'Antiracist Baby', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781654045003 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Teach your child to be antiracist and you change the future',
        text: 'Babies are not born racist. Children do not wake up one day with opinions about people of color unless they have soaked up those opinions from the people around them. Racism is taught, not inherited, and the same is true of antiracism.\n\nRacists are made, not born. That means an antiracist can be made too.\n\nAs a parent, you hold a great deal of influence. You can teach your child to see the beauty in human differences and to treat those differences as something to celebrate rather than something to fear. You can show them that the color of a person skin does not change their value.\n\nThere is no neutral ground. A child is either nudged toward racist thinking or away from it. With the steps in this piece, you can help your child grow up in a world that treats everyone fairly. If every parent took the same approach, the change across generations would be enormous.\n\nA 2018 review of police stops in New York City found that about eighty eight percent of those stopped were Black or Latino, while only ten percent were white. Roughly seventy percent of those stops involved innocent people.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Help your child see the full range of skin tones',
        text: 'Pretending that skin color does not exist is just as harmful as treating it as a problem. Children need to understand that people come in many shades, and that the shade of a person skin has nothing to do with how they should be treated.\n\nTalk openly about skin color and help your child find the beauty in the variety around them.\n\nA person is measured by what they do and how they treat others, not by the color of their skin. Encourage your child to notice the wide range of skin tones in the world and to appreciate the differences they see.\n\nClaiming to be color blind, Ibram X Kendi has written, is a way of denying what is right in front of you.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Speak up about racism',
        text: 'Racism is a global problem. Staying quiet about it, or letting racist moments pass without comment, sends the message that it does not matter. It does matter. It matters a great deal.\n\nA big part of raising an antiracist child is showing them that racism exists, that it is harmful, and that it has to stop. Use your words when you see something racist. Talk about what you see and hear, and help your child understand why those thoughts or actions are wrong.\n\nChildren need to see the harm racism causes and to understand why things have to change.\n\nRacism has to be named, called out, and discussed. If we do not do this work as a community and as parents, it will keep being just as violent and destructive as it has been for centuries.\n\nThe conversation can feel heavy, and it is fair to wonder whether such a topic is appropriate for a child. If you want your child to be antiracist, though, you have to teach them what racism is and why it is wrong from an early age.\n\nA US study found that job applications with names that sound Black were roughly fifty percent less likely to get a callback than applications with names that sound traditionally white.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Policies, not just people, shape inequality',
        text: 'It is a fact that some people get more of what they want, while others get less. The gap is not always about effort or luck. The rules in place often decide who gets more and who gets less, and that is not a fair system. It is a racist and prejudiced one.\n\nPolicies frequently target people of color and minority groups in unfair ways.\n\nThe problem is not the people so much as the policies that govern them. These rules push certain groups, often people of color, into positions where they have to work ten times harder for a quarter of the reward.\n\nTeach your child that the world is not always fair, and that policies can be stacked against certain groups. Show them that people of color are often the ones hurt by these rules. The antiracist babies raised today may grow up to push for changes that finally bring justice and fairness to everyone.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Under the surface, we are all the same',
        text: 'Ibram X Kendi argues that children should learn to see and value differences in skin color and culture, and that they should also learn that under all those differences, we are simply human.\n\nHelp your child see that we are all different, and that underneath those differences we are all human.\n\nWe are born the same way. We live our lives, and we die. The only difference is what happens in between. We all have a heart that beats, blood that moves, a brain that thinks, and feelings that matter.\n\nWherever a person is born, whatever color their skin, whatever culture they belong to, whatever language they speak, they are still a person. Beneath everything, we are the same.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Celebrate what makes us different',
        text: 'Diversity is something to enjoy. It is a way to learn something new. Encourage your child to lean into differences, to learn about cultures they have not seen, to pick up words in other languages, and to ask questions.\n\nThe antiracist baby does not think any group is better or worse. They love a world that is truly diverse, as Ibram X Kendi has written.\n\nTeaching a child from a young age that we are all human and all equal pushes back against the racist idea that some groups are worth more than others.\n\nHelp your child find the wonder in different cultures. Show them dances, songs, and languages from around the world and let them react with curiosity rather than judgment. Every culture is unique, beautiful, and just as important as the next.\n\nEncourage your child to learn about new cultures, art, and languages, and to enjoy the experience.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Admit mistakes and learn from them',
        text: 'Being antiracist means being honest about the times you have said something racist or thought in a racist way. Questioning long held beliefs is one of the foundations of breaking racism down. Learning and changing takes courage, and it is how a more open society gets built.\n\nTeach your child that admitting a racist thought or word is the first step toward doing better.\n\nAs your child grows, encourage them to own up to the moments when they have thought or said something racist. Talk through why it was wrong, and help them understand. The way to push racism out of our lives is through understanding and education.\n\nThe point is not to make a child feel guilty for every slip, but to teach them and help them see the mistake. Children are still learning, and the racist world they live in will leave a mark sometimes. The goal is to give them the strength and the courage to speak up and learn from what they got wrong.\n\nRacism grows when we do not question our thoughts and words. Education is the lever that moves the world.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Encourage your child to stay curious',
        text: 'The antiracist baby is always learning, changing, and growing, as Ibram X Kendi has written.\n\nAs a parent, you can encourage your child to be curious about the people and the world around them. Curiosity makes it easy to ask questions, pick up new ideas, and grow into an open minded adult.\n\nThere is a great deal to learn from other cultures, and a curious child will keep finding new things to explore and new people to meet. A curious child learns to be antiracist because they treat differences as a source of wonder rather than a reason to be afraid.\n\nEncourage your child to ask questions and to meet new people.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Look beyond the surface',
        text: 'The antiracist baby believes that, in time, we will beat racism. They do not judge a book by its cover. They get to know the person as a fellow human being, treat them with equal respect, and wait to see the whole story before forming an opinion.\n\nRaising a child to understand racism gives real hope that the problem can be solved. The antiracist baby is a key part of a major cultural shift.\n\nThe antiracist baby will be part of the reason racism finally ends. They bring an attitude of curiosity, they celebrate differences, they call out racism when they see it, and they understand that the problem is not people in general but the policies that shape the system.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Racism has been part of human history for as long as records exist, and it has done enormous harm. If we want to root it out, we have to start with how we raise our children. We have to raise a generation of antiracist babies who will grow up and challenge unfair policies, celebrate differences, and break the cycle.\n\nOur children really are the future, and teaching them that racism does not belong in the world is a real step toward ending the oppression and discrimination that has hurt people for centuries.\n\nPractical steps include talking with your child about skin color and cultural differences and inviting their questions. Silence lets racism grow. Read books and watch shows that highlight different cultures. When something about racism comes up in the news, be honest about what happened and resist the urge to soften the story.\n\nKeep reading to the end.'
      }
    ]
  },
  'anxiety-in-relationship.json': {
    base: { id: 'anxiety-in-relationship', title: 'Anxiety in Relationship', author: '', type: 'summary', addedAt: 1781647682951 },
    chapters: [
      {
        title: 'Close relationships can lift you up or hold you back',
        text: 'Relationships are the source of our greatest joy and our deepest wounds. People in healthy relationships tend to be happier and more likely to succeed, and the opposite is just as true. A painful relationship can box you in and hold you back.\n\nChoose a partner carefully if you want to enjoy long term success.\n\nThe pattern shows up in every kind of close bond, but it is most obvious in romantic relationships, where two people get closer to each other than they get to almost anyone else.\n\nGiven how much relationships shape our lives, it pays to know how to keep them healthy. Part of that work is removing anything that drags them down, and anxiety is one of the biggest drag factors. This summary focuses on anxiety in relationships and how to handle it.\n\nYou will learn what anxiety does to you and to your partner, and how to manage it when it shows up. Negative emotions and jealousy also get into intimate relationships, and later chapters cover practical ways to deal with them on both sides of the bond. We will also look at attachment styles and the way good listening can change a relationship for the better.'
      },
      {
        title: 'A little anxiety is normal, and it can be managed',
        text: 'Newlyweds and long term couples will almost certainly hit rough patches, and anxiety is one of the most common causes. Anxiety can whisper that your partner no longer likes you, that they have lost interest, or that someone else has taken your place.\n\nAnxiety makes you suspicious of every move your partner makes. You start seeing signs in things that mean nothing, and the worry grows. A simple example is a woman working late to meet a deadline, and her partner reading it as a sign that she is seeing someone else. At its worst, anxiety can lead to stalking, snooping through devices, and a constant need to know what the other person is doing at every moment.\n\nIt is normal for anxious feelings to surface from time to time in a relationship.\n\nWhichever way the anxiety shows up, it should not be allowed to run the show. The skill is to keep it in check, since letting it loose can turn a happy relationship sour. No one likes to be accused of something they did not do, and the suspicion can become a self fulfilling prophecy.\n\nThere are practical ways to share your feelings with your partner so the insecurity loses its grip and the relationship stays healthy. The rest of this summary walks through them.\n\nYou do not have to be the anxious one in the relationship. Living with an anxious partner can be exhausting, and the partner is rarely acting on purpose. The summary also covers the right response and posture for the calmer partner, so the relationship does not get hurt by reactions that come from a place of frustration.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Insecurity is the engine of relationship anxiety',
        text: 'Feeling inadequate or unworthy is one of the main drivers of relationship anxiety. Sometimes the feeling comes from a real situation. Sometimes it comes from imagined fear. When the cause is real, the partner is doing something that feeds the insecurity, and the only way to find it is to look honestly at your own thoughts. Once the source is clear, the next step is to talk about it.\n\nWhen the cause of the insecurity is real, talking it through with your partner is the right move.\n\nHow you talk about it matters. Blaming your partner or making accusations you cannot back up will hurt the relationship, and it is worth resisting the urge to do either. The healthier move is to stay calm and collected.\n\nMany anxious people struggle to say what they are feeling, and that is normal. If you can see the physical, behavioral, or emotional signs of anxiety in your partner, the kindest thing you can do is gently invite them to open up. When an anxious person is trying to explain, the best gift is a listening ear. Try to listen without getting defensive.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Your attachment style can build or break the relationship',
        text: 'Attachment styles are formed early, based on the kind of relationship a child had with a primary caregiver. Knowing your own style, and your partner, is a good way to understand each other better and to strengthen the relationship. Psychologists have grouped attachment into four categories, and it helps to figure out which one fits you and which one fits your partner.\n\nSecure attachment. People in this group had a stable, supportive childhood. They saw their parents as a base from which to go out and explore the world, and they bring that steadiness into adult relationships. They are supportive of their partners and willing to ask for help when they need it.\n\nAnxious preoccupied attachment. People with this style often look to their partner to fill in a sense of being complete. They can struggle with identity, and they tend to be hard to satisfy in a relationship.\n\nDismissive avoidant attachment. People in this group tend to downplay the importance of close bonds and can pull away from the people they love. They are the ones who insist that they do not care when a partner threatens to leave, even when their behavior in the relationship is harmful.\n\nFearful avoidant attachment. People in this group live in a kind of tension. They believe that closeness is necessary for a real connection, but they are also afraid of being hurt. They tend to experience emotional swings and find it hard to be open with a partner about what they need.\n\nA secure attachment pattern leaves a person confident, self possessed, and able to connect with others while looking after their own needs, as Theresa Miller has written.\n\nAttachment styles are set in childhood, and they can be shaped by past relationships. Someone who was once secure can become fearful avoidant after a partner cheats, for example. The reverse is also true if they meet a partner who helps them feel safe again. Whatever your style is right now, becoming more secure is still possible.\n\nAnxious people benefit from learning to communicate clearly with their partner, and good communication reduces anxiety for both sides.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Good listening is the fastest way out of a fight',
        text: 'Conflict is a normal part of any relationship. No matter how long two people have been together, something will eventually spark a disagreement. Putting two humans together and expecting constant peace is unrealistic, and a big reason for the arguments is that both partners are being honest and open with each other. When people are being real, friction is almost inevitable, since no two people are ever the same. Conflict is also a way to learn more about each other.\n\nLong, heated fights between people who have been together for a while are a different story. Some friction is normal, but it should not last forever. Over time, partners should know each other well enough to work through the rough patches easily. That is the theory. In practice, close to half of all marriages in the United States end in divorce.\n\nThe reality is that some people simply have not learned the skills for handling hard conversations.\n\nThe roots of conflict run deep, and they sit in how emotionally safe each person feels.\n\nIf arguments in your relationship keep getting heated, before you blame your partner, make sure you have the skills for resolving the conflict in the first place.\n\nOne of those skills is good listening. Arguments are full of emotion, and people will keep talking until they feel heard. The best thing you can do when your partner is angry is to stay quiet and listen. It is hard at first, but it gets easier with practice, and you will be glad you did it. While you listen, try to go beyond the words and read the nonverbal cues your partner is giving you.\n\nWhen you really listen to your partner, you are showing them that you care, as Theresa Miller has written.\n\nA 2014 study from the University of North Carolina at Greensboro found that American women who married or moved in with a partner at eighteen had a divorce rate of about sixty percent, while those who waited until twenty three had a divorce rate closer to thirty percent.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Every relationship goes through five stages',
        text: 'Long term relationships tend to pass through five stages. If you are committed, engaged, or married, the framework is worth knowing. The stages are not optional, and many couples worry that something is wrong with them or with their partner when the relationship moves from one stage to the next. Knowing the stages ahead of time can keep a relationship from getting stuck in a toxic place.\n\nThe romance stage. This is usually the first stage, and it can last anywhere from two months to two years. The couple is high on the in love feeling, and the partner can seem like a flawless, perfect human. The phrase love is blind probably comes from this stage.\n\nThe power struggle stage. As the high of the romance stage fades, the couple starts to notice the rough edges and the differences. Those differences can lead to a power struggle, since both people try to push the other to become their ideal partner. A lot of relationships end in this stage. To survive it, the couple has to learn to agree to disagree, or to find a middle ground where both can be happy.\n\nThe stability stage. This is the natural follow up to the power struggle. The couple is no longer surprised by the differences, and they are learning to live with them and to keep the relationship as happy as possible.\n\nThe commitment stage. Ideally, this is the stage where a couple gets married, but many couples tie the knot in the romance stage and regret it when they hit the power struggle. In the commitment stage, the couple is happy with the deepening bond. They are starting to find a balance between love, belonging, power, freedom, and fun. They begin to reconnect with the friendships and commitments they may have set aside in the romance stage.\n\nThe co creation stage. This is the final stage, and not every couple reaches it. Couples who do reach it have become a real team. They are ready to take on bigger projects together, such as raising children, building a family business, or facing a serious illness, as a single unit.\n\nThe romance stage is short, but its purpose is to give the couple a taste of what the relationship can become if they keep working on it.\n\nThe pace at which couples move through the stages varies a lot, and it is normal to move back and forth between them.'
      },
      {
        title: 'Conclusion',
        text: 'Long term relationships can lose their spark over time. What should you do when the spark fades and you start losing interest in your partner? First, know that it is a normal experience. It does not mean you have stopped loving them, and it is not a reason to start looking elsewhere.\n\nThe drift usually happens once a couple is married or has been together for a long time, and they slip into the idea that date nights and dressing up for each other are things of the past. That mindset needs to be challenged early, since the fastest way to recover the spark is to recreate the dating days.\n\nRemember the early days. The dinner dates, the weekend movies, the concerts you went to hand in hand. The same things can be done again, with a little planning. Step outside the routine. Make time for dates. If you do not have young children, plan a trip for the two of you. With the internet, it is easy to find a comfortable place to stay in a place you have always wanted to visit.\n\nPractical steps include making time to look your best for your partner. The effort is appreciated, and it helps the two of you reconnect on a physical and emotional level.\n\nKeep reading to the end.'
      }
    ]
  }
};
